@startuml Evaluation Model - Throughput
!theme plain
title Network Throughput - Transactions Per Second (TPS)
package "Validator Configurations" {
    rectangle "4 Validators" as config4 {
        card "TPS: 850" as tps4 #lightblue
        card "Latency: 65ms" as lat4
    }
    rectangle "7 Validators" as config7 {
        card "TPS: 1200" as tps7 #lightgreen
        card "Latency: 48ms" as lat7
    }
    rectangle "10 Validators" as config10 {
        card "TPS: 1450" as tps10 #yellow
        card "Latency: 52ms" as lat10
    }
    rectangle "15 Validators" as config15 {
        card "TPS: 1650" as tps15 #orange
        card "Latency: 78ms" as lat15
    }
    rectangle "20 Validators" as config20 {
        card "TPS: 1550" as tps20 #red
        card "Latency: 125ms" as lat20
    }
}
config4 -[hidden]right-> config7
config7 -[hidden]right-> config10
config10 -[hidden]right-> config15
config15 -[hidden]right-> config20
note bottom
    **Throughput Analysis:**
    **Optimal Point: 10-15 Validators**
    • Maximum TPS: ~1650 (15 validators)
    • Best latency: 48ms (7 validators)
    • Ideal trade-off: 10 validators
    **Limiting Factors:**
    1. PBFT communication overhead: O(n²)
    2. Network bandwidth
    3. Node processing capacity
    **Observations:**
    • >15 validators: degradation due to overhead
    • <7 validators: lower fault tolerance
    • Main bottleneck: PBFT consensus
    **Possible Optimizations:**
    → Regional validator sharding
    → Transaction parallelization
    → Optimized BFT (HotStuff, Tendermint)
end note
@enduml
